{
  "texts": [
    "Their results indicate that all of these factors are important drivers of public support.",
    "Focusing on partisan differences in source cue framing effects, the authors indicate that Democratic (Republican) respondents are more likely to support Democratic (Republican) state legislators' bills.",
    "Using LAS-SOplus, we, however, cannot find any significant subgroup effects among partisan differences.",
    "Christenson, Goldfarb and Kriners' (id35) study use a US nationally representative sample to conduct a survey experiment testing how information about economic and environmental costs and benefits affects fracking support.",
    "Their results provide limited evidence of motivated partisan reasoning as framing effects are most considerable for respondents with conflicting partisanship and climate change beliefs."
  ]
